<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-646-080  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 646 080.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Sept 12 1989 v3 n32 p54(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The 'Hyper' word from Apple.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Waring, Becky.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Product:   Hypercard (Data base management system) (books).andO;Topic:     BooksReviewProgramming.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>The 'Hyper' word from AppleandM;Mac programmers have long been familiar with Apple's Human InterfaceGuidelines, which describe, protect and even somewhat stifle themuch-ballyhooed Mac interface.andP;  HyperCard, however, broke many of those sameguidelines and has spawned almost as many user inteface variations as stocks.andO;Attempting to organize the chaos, Apple has just released its HyperCard StackDesign Guidelines, sort of a road map to building &quot;Mac-like&quot; stacks.andO;Published by Addison-Wesley, the paperback covers such topics as navigation,placement of text, music, sound and, most interestingly, what subject matteris appropriate for a stack.andP;  There's also a chapter that attempts to describethe entire process of stack building, which would have been much morevaluable with an actual example.andM;The book gives a lot of sound advice and is a model of clarity andpreservation, just like a good stuck.andP;  It's well worth the $16.95 investment.andO;</TEXT></DOC>